----------------

usage: ./rlzbyte64 {file of filenames}

Above, "file of filenames" should contain two file names, one on each line. (An example called SARS.txt is included).
The first file, e.g. X.txt, should contain the RLZ dictionary string (aka the reference string).
The second file, e.g. Y.txt, should contain the string you want to factorize against the reference.

The suffix array of the first file X.txt is expected to be present and should be called X.txt.sa.
You can generate the suffix array for X.txt with the gensa program included in this package:
./gensa ./X.txt ./X.txt.sa

The rlzbyte64 program will only count the number of factors, not output them.
